comments.body: A lot of completion happens in bulk, though, right? It might be good to figure out for sure how some of these happened.

@hackartisan That's a good point about bulk completion. @kelea99 and I are reviewing these and will reach out to stakeholders for some of these. One of the big sets of items in this state are an ephemera collection where items were completed before the files were ingested. Excluding those, (and Coins/Issues which are fine without files), I'm not immediately seeing a pattern, so I think in general people aren't bulk completing items without files (though maybe they bulk completed collections that had a couple of items without files).

@hackartisan , yes! it does. I also found the same thing as @escowles . No real patterns, save 1 example (and a couple of test/example records).  I should think this could be solved by making clear what the best practices are for completing items in figgy within the documented workflows themselves and training  opportunities for figgy users.  Or perhaps a best practices document for figgy in general?

comments.body:
[![Coverage Status](https://coveralls.io/builds/39636580/badge)](https://coveralls.io/builds/39636580)

Coverage increased (+0.2%) to 96.639% when pulling **6107c3e7d2cef6e2068fefe11eaeb9a742aa8970 on 2401-account-link** into **f3d8b3a3ecc85d7745adef6a798ef4cc8d3bc754 on main**.

Some thoughts:
1. Dropdown with one option: Your account -> `Library Card login` ? (redirects to the exlibris library card view)
Keep `Bookmarks` and `Search history` with the login as it is in this pr.

2. Dropdown with two options: Your account -> `Library Card login` and -> `Catalog Login` (This way we dont need to have separate login for bookmarks and search history).
             
What do you think? I understand the difficulty differentiating between the exlibris view and the catalog. 

Also can we add an external link icon to the link that takes the user to the exlibris library card?
@axamei if/when you have a chance can you provide some feedback?

I kept the title "Your Account" since that's what was used before for the in-site page and it's the same sort of data. The new page is titled "My Library Card" but I'm not sure if people will know what that means in the context of this UI? I think adding login buttons to the bookmarks and search history pages gives a little hint that there will be saved data there if they want to log in. If this isn't enough of a hint then maybe a full line of text below the page heading like `Log in to save or view saved bookmarks` would be better. If we moved it back into the "your account" dropdown I'm not really sure where it should redirect -- I guess just always to the page you were on? I'm not sure it's clear to the user what is the utility of the catalog login.

The double "Your account" labels might be confusing. And, the "My Library Card" page does not give them access to their catalog account to view saved bookmarks and search history. Maybe in the submenu we can have the following options? 
![Screen Shot 2021-05-12 at 11 20 46 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8161144/118002331-83b08180-b315-11eb-8299-c4a1d5ddfe34.png)

And asking the patron to click 2 login buttons seems unnecessary. Maybe we can add the 2 login options directly in the bookmarks and search history pages? 
![Screen Shot 2021-05-12 at 11 30 16 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8161144/118002299-7c897380-b315-11eb-938a-6c777769a1dc.png)
(fyi did this quickly in devtools to illustrate)

@axamei Thanks for these suggestions. So the bookmark / search history links under "your account" would just go to the page, without logging in first? And would the links to those pages then be removed from the subnav?

The site does save bookmarks and search history in session even if you're not logged in and even if you don't have an account. I wonder if that's one reason bookmarks was listed separately to begin with. But I'm not sure this distinction is important; I think they're okay under the "Your account" menu.

@hackartisan the bookmark / search history links under "your account" would go to the page like in the screenshot. The links in the info text are the ones that will direct the user to login when they click on them. https://catalog.princeton.edu/users/sign_in

@hackartisan Yes, they would like to the bookmark/search history pages without having to login first. We could remove the redundant links in the search header. These are usually decisions I make after looking at analytics. Initially, we can leave the redundant links in, add some event tracking, and then evaluate the removal of the subheader links.

Prior to this PR, "Bookmarks" was in the subnav and "Search History" was in the account dropdown. In this PR I moved "Search History" out to the subnav for symmetry with "Bookmarks" But it sounds like the Information Architecture makes more sense for them to both be in the account dropdown. I'd rather not add Search History to the subnav only to potentially remove it again down the line. In which case Bookmarks would be in both places, but Search History only in the account dropdown. I'm thinking we should just go ahead and remove Bookmarks from the subnav to have that symmetry.

I think we should keep bookmarks in the subnav. I believe users are used to see the count in the parenthesis when they bookmark a record. If we remove it from the subnav then they would have to check all the time in the dropdown for the count. But this is my user experience as a user. Maybe it is not a big issue for the rest of the users not to have the bookmarks (n) in the subnav.
